String Class:

The String class in Java is a fundamental class that represents a sequence of characters.
It is used extensively in Java programming and provides various features to manipulate and
process text data. Here are some of the basic features of the String class:

concat(): String Concatenation: The String class provides the "+" operator for concatenating two or
more strings together. concat() method also do the same thing
For example:

        String str1 = "Hello";
        String str2 = "World";
        String str3 = str1 + " " + str2; // Output: "Hello World"
        String str3 = str1.concat(str2)

String Length: The String class provides the length() method that returns the number of characters
in the string. For example:

        String str = "Hello World";
        int length = str.length(); // Output: 11

String Comparison: The String class provides the equals() method for comparing two strings for equality.
For example:
        String str1 = "Hello";
        String str2 = "Hello";
        boolean isEqual = str1.equals(str2); // Output: true

String Manipulation: The String class provides various methods to manipulate strings such as
toUpperCase(), toLowerCase(), trim(), replace(), and many more.

toUpperCase() and toLowerCase():
        String str = "Hello World";
        String upperCaseStr = str.toUpperCase();
        String lowerCaseStr = str.toLowerCase();
        System.out.println(upperCaseStr); // Output: "HELLO WORLD"
        System.out.println(lowerCaseStr); // Output: "hello world"

trim():
        public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "  Hello World   ";
        String trimmedStr = str.trim();
        System.out.println(trimmedStr); // Output: "Hello World"

replace():
        String str = "Hello World";
        String replacedStr = str.replace("World", "Java");
        System.out.println(replacedStr); // Output: "Hello Java"

charAt():
        String str = "Hello";
        char firstChar = str.charAt(0);
        System.out.println(firstChar); // Output: 'H'

